es the literary context of the myth itself. It also examines the strengths and weaknesses of these psychological interpretations (five Freudian and six Jungian) of the Eros and Psyche myth in order to lay the groundwork for an interpretation which (1) avoids the rigidity of both Freudian and Jungian dogma and (2) restores the myth to its rightful literary and religious context — something which has been ignored by most psychological interpretations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aApuleius. Metamorphoses. 0aLove. 0aPsychology. 0aReligion. 0aSoul. 4aPsychology. 4aReligion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh  aEros.  aFreud.  aFreudian.  aJung.  aJungian.  aeros and psyche.  afolklore.  amythology.  apsyche.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920804940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208049423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208049/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles